        "title": "Mastery learning",
        "text": "Mastery learning (or, as it was initially called, \"learning for mastery\") is an instructional strategy and educational philosophy, first formally proposed by Benjamin Bloom in 1968. Mastery learning maintains that students must achieve a level of mastery (e.g., 90% on a knowledge test) in prerequisite knowledge before moving forward to learn subsequent information. If a student does not achieve mastery on the test, they are given additional support in learning and reviewing the information and then tested again. This cycle continues until the learner accomplishes mastery, and they may then move on to the next stage - [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mastery_learning wikipedia]"
